<H2>Bounds built into the MDS code </H2>

The MDS code computes the bounds or known dimensions as indicated above in (1)-(7).  It
also modifies the lower bound to indicate the trivial fact that the
spline space contains all polynomials of degree <em>d</em>.  To
turn the feature on and off click on the button labeled
<em>Bounds</em> in the sixth row of the control panel.  When active,
the feature prints 3 numbers at the top of the drawing window: a lower
bound, the dimension (when available) and an upper bound, connected by
the appropriate algebraic relations.  However, when supersmoothness
conditions are present, the upper and lower bounds are only
<b>conjectured</b> and therefore may be false.  If there are
inconsistencies, like the upper bound being less that the lower
bound, or less than the dimension, the figures are shown in red.

<p> The MDS code computes a
conjectured lower bound <em>lb</em>.  Let <em>mu<sub>e</sub></em>
denote the (super)smoothness across an interior edge <em>e</em>, and 
<em>rho<sub>v</sub></em>
the (super)smoothness around an interior vertex <em>v</em>.  Moreover, let
<em>v<sub>e</sub></em> and <em>w<sub>e</sub></em>
denote the two vertices of an interior edge <em>e</em>. (One
or both may be boundary vertices.)  

